    "summary": "Sidebar may be dropped -- simpler HTMX nav pattern instead",
    "content": "Carson, quick update -- Heydon made a case against the sidebar layout I proposed to you earlier. His argument: a persistent sidebar is a spatial metaphor that doesn't work for screen readers, and keeping a single `<nav>` landmark in the header is simpler and more accessible.\n\nIf we go that direction, the HTMX pattern simplifies significantly. Instead of sidebar links targeting a content panel, we'd have standard header nav links that do full page navigations, HTMX-boosted with `hx-boost=\"true\"` on the `<body>` or `<nav>` for speed. Each GTD view is a full page, same handler pattern we already use (check HX-Request, return fragment or full page).\n\nThis is actually more aligned with hypermedia principles -- each view has its own URL, navigation is standard link behavior enhanced by HTMX for speed, no client-side routing metaphor. The sidebar approach was leaning toward SPA-style content swapping.\n\nWhat's your take? Does the simpler header-nav approach feel more natural from an HTMX perspective?"
  }
}
